segments.text: One, two, three, four.
One, two, three.
Can we do that too?
One, two, three, four.
This is December the 12th, year 2000, down in the Jack Kenny Williams Administration Building.
I have the honor and pleasure of chatting with Mary Ruth Patronella, whose title now is... Assistant to the Dean.
Assistant to the Dean of Agriculture.
want to record her memories of what it has been like to be a member of the staff here for a good many years.
First, introduce yourself to anyone who might read or hear this.
Where did you grow up?
What did your family do?
Where did you go to school?
And so forth.
OK.
I was born in Edge, Texas, which is in the northern part of the county.
I went to school at Edge.
They had elementary and about two grades, I believe, in high school.
Then I came to Brine High and graduated from Brine.
What year?
How many in the senior class?
I could find that out, but I don't have it from memory because I have the program for our graduation.
You lived out in the country?
I lived in the country and rode the bus to Brine.
After I graduated, I didn't feel like that I could go to college, and I didn't have a job.
Being out in the country, I guess I just didn't know what I was supposed to do.
So I went back to Bryan High and took postgraduate work and worked in the principal's office.
My daddy knew D.W. Williams, and he asked Mr. Williams about
my finding employment in the animal science department he was head.
And he said he needed someone who had experience.
And I had no experience.
I don't really remember how I
but got a job in the division of poultry science, which is part of the experiment station located on the F&B station.
But my first job was at the poultry house to count egg records, where they had sheets for a hen and made stick marks.
And I counted those stick marks first.
And when did you go to work on the campus?
That was December of 39.
December of 39.
Do you remember what your pay was?
The only question I'm going to ask about money, do you remember what your first pay was?
I'm trying to think.
I think it was $2 a day, and we worked five and a half days, so I probably made about $11 a week.
And you lived at home.
I lived with friends in Bryanville.
Oh, okay.
How did you get back and forth on the campus?
We used to have carpools.
And the car would be full.
People would go around to the different homes and get a car full and come to Texas A&M.
Describe the campus in those days.
What was it like?
What were the major buildings?
Well, where I was is out at F&B.
And there was poultry, dairy, and swine.
And they each had these frame houses, offices.
And the person in charge of the unit was called chief.
Chief.
Chief.
Chief of the division.
Who was the, was poultry science even a separate department then?
It was a division of the Texas Agricultural Experiment Station.
And it was before the coordination of teaching, research, and extension.
That didn't happen, I think, until about 1947.
And your normal work day was an eight to five?
Yes, sir.
Eight to five.
What about lunch?
Well, I guess we carried our lunch.
We had sack lunches.
How was a young woman treated on the campus then?
Well, I think, well, you know, of course, as I say, I was out off the campus, really, to start.
So you didn't see many students?
No, I didn't see many students out there.
You were counting these eggs.
That was part of the experiment, the search?
Yes, sir.
Was there a particular person whose work y'all were watching?
We did, I don't know whether you remember Russell Couch and Lee James?
Mm-hmm.
were there and when the war started they had commissions and went into the service.
So what happened to your accounts?
Then we had some people come in and I'm trying to think one of them was named Dr. Mellis and then someone named Baker.
How's Mellis spelled?
M-E-L-L-A-I-S-S I think I'm not sure I can't remember but I remember his name was Vivian
And he said, you know, that was a lady's name and he didn't, he wanted to be called V.H.
instead of Vivian.
When you started work, the war in Europe already was underway.
Yes, sir.
How much did y'all, did that affect your life here in Bryan and the campus?
And there's gas rationing, so.
Well, no, no, not yet.
In 39 and 40.
No, no, not then.
But the war, you know, affects.
During the war, they had a policy that they changed the time you went to work or you could go to work from 8 to 7.
How long did you stay with Polter Science?
Until October of.
41, I believe that that's.
And then, so what was your?
Then my husband was called into the service.
And, no, I'm telling you wrong, Doctor.
It wasn't 41.
It must have been later than that.
So when, you got married when?
In December, I mean October 1941.
And your husband, what was his profession?
He owned a restaurant in Brown.
At that time.
Okay.
But you continued to work here on the campus.
Continued to work on the campus.
Do you remember where you were when you heard the news on December 7, 1941?
Yes, sir, I do.
Describe that, please.
We were, my parents lived in the country.
We went out there every Sunday or every other Sunday.
And we were on our way to Edge when we heard that about,
Pearl Harbor being bombed.
Did you or your husband or anyone else guess as to how your life might be changed by that?
Not at the time, I don't think.
Did you know where Pearl Harbor was?
Not really.
Not really.
I didn't.
When I heard it, I just knew it was somewhere on the other side of the world.
All right.
And was he in the reserve?
No, sir.
He was drafted.
drafted and your new task then that your second slot here on the campus was where?
Your second job.
In the Department of Animal Science, Animal Husbandry at the time.
And where physically?
Animal Industries Building.
The first job I had there though was bookkeeper for the Meats Laboratory.
Who was the department head then?
I'm trying to think.
Seemed like Mr. Dahlberg was interim.
And a young man named O.D.
Butler, was he?
Well, he was, when he came back from the war, he, Dr. Jack Miller was head.
And there were about three people there that Dr. Miller suggested they go to graduate school.
And one of them was O.D.
Was O.D.
And Bill Warren and George Robertson.
All right, so you worked there throughout the war.
That puts you on the campus.
Describe what happened here during the war.
What was the campus like?
Well, you know, it's hard for me to remember exactly what it was like, Dr. Monroe.
I know that, of course, a lot of the students, you know, had to go to the service.
And I don't know what their enrollment really was.
Were you as a woman treated politely here on campus?
I think I've always been treated politely.
And so the I know that the campus went to a trimester system and they went to class 12 months a year to get everybody out faster.
Did the enrollment go down?
You know, when I started, as I say, I was a bookkeeper in the meats lab.
And they were killing cattle for the dining halls, for the markets and brine, because there was no other slaughter plant.
And we had about 220 lockers down in the basement.
And so we were, I was really involved in that.
And we made a report to the board of directors every month.
We would bind up a financial report.
And so there would have been a big cash flow.

And I would come to the this building where the fiscal office and bring the money you know that we would our sales fund and we had a cash riding machine and we had someone buying cattle and the department paid him a dollar a head to do that was Mr. Yeager.
Yeager?
Yeager.
Y-E-A-G-E-R?
Yes, sir.
And he, W.O.
Yeager.
And I could write, had the check writing machine and pay him and then get reimbursed.
And this was not part of any research or anything.
No.
This was a cash operation.
This was an operation.
I don't know how they got started, but they had been without someone to do that work for about two months.
When I came over, they had some gentleman that was doing it first.
Where was the slaughtering operation located?
West of the tracks?
No, it was over here in the Animal Industries building.
Oh, okay.
There were those holding pens beside the building and the killing floor and cutting room.
Who did that?
Were they hired or were they students?
No, there was a staff.
Okay.
And that went on through the war?
Yes, sir.
I'm not sure when they... Well, they still have some, but they... Then they got to have the co-op, I believe, has a slaughter plant or something.
And the lockers, they took all those out.
The range line ecology and management is in that department, in that building now.
Now, they bought the cattle from this general area.
I suppose so.
A wide variety of cattle?
No specific?
No specific.
And your task continued through the war.
Well, there was a time when the animal science department didn't have a secretary.
So I go up to the departments
head's office and I become the secretary and they hired someone to take my place as bookkeeper.
Oh okay and you who was the department head then when you were the department secretary?
Part of the time it was Dr. Jack Miller and as I say he went he left here I'm not sure when and went to Tennessee
and came back as department head.
I think when it was, when he came back it was when they coordinated the research, teaching, and extension.
Describe the variety of tasks that the departmental secretary had to handle.
Well, we did, we took shorthand, we filed, answered the phone,
And describe what kind of typewriter you used.
Well, I had a manual typewriter first.
And we had, you know, correcting those copies that you had to have carbon paper wasn't too much fun.
Now, you had taken typing and shorthand at Bryan High.
What kind of work hours did the departmental secretary have to put in?
We put in eight hours.
And at that, we finally got to where only one girl and one faculty member had to be at work on Saturdays.
We took turns doing that.
And you were still living out in the country?
No, I was married then and living in Bryan.
Oh, you were living in.
And during the war, with gas rationing and so forth, describe how that changed your routine.
I managed okay with the rationing.
I guess we just didn't drive too much.
When I went to California, I went up to the rationing board and got the ration to drive to California.
So I drove our car all the way from here to California, and about that time they reduced the number of gallons you could get per coupon, but I still made it all right.
Now, were you going out there to see your husband?
Yes.
He was in Army?
Army.
Army.
And you didn't drive by yourself.
He had a friend whose wife was in Illinois.
She rode the train to Hearn, and I picked her up, and she went with me.
Do you remember how long it took you to drive it?
We drove to Midland, I think, one day, and about Mesa, Arizona the next, and then into Los Angeles the following day, about three days.
And was he going overseas, or had he already... At that time, he wasn't.
They were a training cadre.
But then he was moved to Oregon, and he was one of the ones that they took out of that...
and filled a unit that was going overseas.
And served in the Pacific?
No, in Europe, in Italy.
In Italy?
Oh, oh.
So instead of California to the Pacific, he went to... We came back home, had a little bit of time to come back home and drive the car home.
And then he went, in about six days, he went back to be shipped to overseas.
As far as you can recall, other than gas, what other things were most hard to obtain during the war?
One was sugar, shoes.
I may still have some coupons.
What about nylon stockings?
Well, I don't really remember much about that, probably.
Describe the area around the campus.
What was College Station like during those years?
Well, if you, when I think of it, this building kind of sat out here by itself.
The Animal Industries Building and Scotes Hall and maybe some buildings that used to be the Experiment Station headquarters.
It was certainly not built up like it is today.
Where did you park your car?
Over by the building.
Right behind the building.
And I got a station wagon without power steering one time, and when they started
you know, giving people assigned parking spaces.
Dr. Butler gave me one in front of the Animal Industries building.
And I didn't want that because it was a little hard for me to park it.
So I asked him if I could just not have a parking place, and I still parked over by the building.
He always said, if you got here early enough, you found a parking place.
So I usually did that.
Now, when you first came over to animal science, who was the dean of agriculture then?
Dr. Kyle, Dean Kyle.
Describe him.
We don't know much about Dean Kyle.
Well, I remember him coming to my office and telling me how he appreciated what I was doing with the meat slab work.
And of course, I didn't know him very well either.
Physically, what did he look like?
Big, small?
Seems to me like, I really can't say, but we've got pictures of him back here in the office.
Outgoing personality?
Shy?
What?
Well, you know, really, I didn't have that much contact with him.
I just remember him coming in my office and
letting me know that he appreciated what I was doing.
Who was the next dean?
I believe it was Shepardson.
Describe him.
What was he like?
Well, of course, being where I was, I didn't have much.
I've got this for you that gives you the time for these deans.
I'd have to look at it myself to really...
He's 44 to 55.
When the veterans came back, well let's see, in your family, when did the key men in your life come back?
October, I believe, of 45.

uh and I hope no injuries well he was he did get the Purple Heart and the Oakleaf Cluster but it wasn't anything that was severe shot through the thigh and then got shrapnel in the shoulder so he went back into the his restaurant a restaurant and you all still lived in town
Did you ever think during that period of stopping work on campus?
No, sir.
Not until my oldest son was born.
That's when I stopped at that time.
And I really didn't have an idea that I would come back.
So I got my teacher retirement money out.
When was that?
That was in December of 49.
And Pat was born 28th of January.
And so you thought you were retiring.
Well, what led you to come back?
Dr. Butler was, Dr. O.D.
Butler was head of the department.
He had someone in the bookkeeping department who wanted to retire.
Her name was Bessie Lou Smith.
And so he called me and asked me if I would come back.
But she wasn't leaving at that point.
So it took about six months before she really left.
And he would call me once in a while and ask me what I was thinking or how I felt about it.
And describe this man, O.D.
Butler.
He was a general.
He was a fine person to work for.
I enjoyed that very much.
See, I went to high school in Orange where he grew up.
I did not know him over there.
I knew his brother who was a very active civic leader.
And so when you said he was general, I know he was a firm person.
Yes, he was.
Did he also know how to relax?
Did he have a sense of humor?
Yes, he did.
And I think he relaxed.
I think he played golf.
But I would go to the department meetings, and he would always tease Dr. Kunkel about not being married.
And he did that to Cliff Laywell.
And he was very outspoken, and he said what he thought.
What were his joys?
What did he enjoy most?
Well, I think he was chair of the Athletic Council.
And I think also while I was working for him, he bought the land that they now own out here.
I probably typed some of those letters.
South of the campus down on Welborn Road.
Yes, sir.
And it belonged to the Jones family.
He and Edsel Jones, his brother-in-law, were buying some of that land together.
Have any idea when that was?
No, sir, I really don't.
Early 50s, maybe?
Probably.
And did he... No, it probably...
I wasn't here in the early 50s, so... Now, when did you come back to work?

uh august of 58 58 might have been later at 50s okay i'm not real sure did he uh put cattle on that land quickly i think i think he did uh again uh dr butler what were some things that he did not want someone in the office staff to do what were some guidelines y'all knew never really had any problem with that i don't think
because I always decided, you know, that I was going to be at work when I was supposed to be at work.
But like, did he allow people to smoke in the office?
Could you drink coffee?
We probably would drink coffee, but I don't remember anybody smoking.
And the Dean of Agriculture, when you came back to work in the late 50s, who, that was Dr. Watkins, Gus Watkins.
Dr. Watkins, one of the
Dean very long, so I didn't have much contact with him.
Dr. Patterson.
Yes, I knew Dr. Patterson.
Dr. Kunkel came over here as associate director of the experiment station, and when Dr. Lewis left, Dr. Patterson came down and was the super dean, where we call it vice chancellor now.
They were called dean, but not, and he would, Dr. Patterson said he wasn't a dean like these other deans here on campus.
In fact, he didn't want his picture hung out here with them.
He was on the other side.
Because he was both dean and director.
And director of the Experiment Station over the Extension Service.
Now, for you at the departmental level,
in the animal science, did that super dean task complicate your job?
See I came over here soon after he was super dean.
Dr. Kunkel came in December of 62 and I came in March of 63.
So I didn't have much time.
For whom did you work?
When I came over here, Dr. Kunkel first as associate director.
Make believe I don't know Harry Kunkel.
Tell me about Harry Kunkel.
Well, Dr. Kunkel, of course, was a professor in animal science and biochemistry and biophysics.
And Dr. Patterson chose him to be associate director.
So he called me one day, I guess around March, before March, and asked me to bring something over here, this building, and I was going to send a runner.
And he told me, no, come yourself.
So I came over, and he said, how would you like to work over here?
And Dr. Butler said that the one he used to be over now was over him and was taking his secretary.
Uh-oh, uh-oh.
And so I came over here at that time.
Describe your duties.
When I came over here, Dr. Patterson was letting Dr. Kunkel pretty much run the experiment station, you know, the experiment station budgets.
And we used to, while we have more people now, we would get the contracts and check those out, write the letters, and they would be signing the contracts and grants
And this office has changed a lot.
We used to have the project records over on the other side.
About how many, how large was the staff in the office when you first came over?
Not very large.
Maybe 10 or so, I don't know.
We had human resources with one man and one,

lady and you were located in this area i was right up right out here um so on the south end of and everyone called it the system building right uh and uh parking was still simple right right um where did y'all eat lunch then still i guess we're bringing our lunch i didn't go anywhere usually at lunch
Well, at the time, when my husband came back, I used to drive down to the restaurant and eat there at lunch.
Now, what was the name of the restaurant?
Sam's Luncheonette.
Where was it located?
At first, it was on Main Street where they took out a lot of buildings, several buildings, and had Woolworth Building, but he was next to First National Bank to start with.
Now, his family, when did they first come to Brazos County?
early this century?
Yes, sir, I would say so.
And what about your family?
My family lived at Edge.
No, but how many generations?
When did the...
I'm not sure.
Did your grandparents live out there?
My grandparents did, but their parents, I think, came from Tennessee or Kentucky.
Back over here, describe Dean Kunkel's personality.
Sense of humor?
I think he has a sense of humor.
And when did he get married?
You said that O.D.
teased him about getting... Well, you know... Was he married?
It was probably around 59.
Okay, that's what I...
I think 59.
I thought so.
Now, he's an Aggie, had lived in one of the project houses, grew up... Is he from Warda?
I know George Kunze... No, sir, he's not.
He's from Arnie.
Oh, that's right, that's right, out on the high plains.
But of German... German descent.
German descent.
The... And you say that he...
Day to day, he ran the experiment station.
And Dr. Patterson, was his office located in this area?
Yes, sir, on the other side, right across the hall over there, where the secretaries are now.
What was his specialty, Dr. Patterson's?
He was a geneticist.
Geneticist.
And this says that he was here until 1967.

about the time you came back to work a man named Earl Rudder came as president do you remember when you first saw him or met him or anything I remember mostly the name and being in a meeting where he spoke and but I didn't have any you know really contacts with
My contacts were with Dean and Director of the Experiment Station, mainly.
Did you ever have any contact, though, with his office staff?
Yes, some.
Who?
Nelda?
Jerry Hunt.
Jerry Hunt, uh-huh.
I believe Jerry Hunt was there.
Describe Jerry.
Well, I remember she was very involved in working for Mr. Rutter, and I've heard tell that Lesters, who was a...
The store sent her dresses to try on that she didn't have to go.
But I think she was, her time was pretty much taken without Mr. Rutter.
Did you see Mr. Rutter moving around this building and around the campus much?
No, sir, I didn't.
I believe he may have moved upstairs, though.
You know, the president's office used to be on the second floor of this building.
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.
but I'm lost on just the timing of that.
The agriculture program during the 60s, did you feel it was growing, making progress?
Oh, yes, sir.
I have brought you something Dr. Kunkel, while he was a super dean,
and he did this report, so I thought you might be interested in some of the things that happened during that time.
Enrollments and budgets and things that came into being for the first time.
The research and extension centers that were built during that time.
And I don't think there's been any other added since those years when they really,
research and extension centers were built.
Did those of you in agriculture in the 60s, did you all feel progress was being made?
Yes, I think so.
And there was growth and so forth.
We got enrollment growth and ranking right up with the top.
Do you remember any fun events, humor?
Christmas parties, birthday parties, what?
I know we had them, but I don't remember any special events, I don't think.
Don't remember any electricity going off?
No.
Somebody forgetting their speech or anything like that?
Do you remember when Mr. Rutter became ill?
I remember him lying in state out here in Rotunda.
